content.thinking:
The user wants two changes:
1. Move iMessage to the end of the PLATFORMS array (last chip)
2. Fix the iMessage demo messages - show only 2 exchanges (user+bot together at same time, then pause, then user+bot again) rather than showing timestamps between each individual message

Let me re-read the demo messages for iMessage:
```typescript
messages: [
  {
    from: "me",
    text: "reschedule my 3pm to tomorrow same time",
    time: "2:58 PM",
    status: "read",
  },
  {
    from: "them",
    text: "done. rescheduled and invite updated",
    time: "2:58 PM",
  },
  {
    from: "me",
    text: "also add a note to call sarah before it",
    time: "2:59 PM",
    status: "read",
  },
  {
    from: "them",
    text: "added. anything else before I let you go?",
    time: "2:59 PM",
  },
],
```

I can see the current structure has four separate messages with individual timestamps. I need to condense this to show just two message exchanges where each exchange groups the user and bot messages together at the same timestamp, creating a cleaner back-and-forth flow.

Looking at how the `IMessageDemo` component groups messages by sender and displays the time from the first message in each group, I realize the grouping logic will separate consecutive messages from the same person. To achieve the desired visual effect of user + bot response appearing under one timestamp, I'd need to adjust how the time grouping works so it doesn't just rely on sender but also considers time proximity. I see the issue now—the current implementation renders a timestamp for every message group, so alternating user and bot messages each get their own time label. What the user actually wants is to group consecutive user-bot exchanges together under a single timestamp, only showing a new time when there's a meaningful pause in the conversation. So instead of timestamps appearing between every message, they'd only appear at the start of each "conversation burst" and after gaps.

The cleanest approach is to modify how timestamps are assigned in the message data itself—I can set the time to undefined for bot responses that are part of the same burst as the preceding user message, so only the user's message time displays. I see the issue now — I need to set `time: undefined` on the bot messages so only the user message time displays for each conversation burst. That way the first exchange shows "2:58 PM" above the user bubble with the bot response below it, then a gap, then "3:04 PM" for the second exchange.

Now I'll update the demo messages to implement this and move iMessage to the end of the platforms list.

